This paper focuses on gender prediction using text data, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of abstract features and transfer learning, which are common topics in machine learning and data mining. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.CY (Computers and Society) are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the limitations of previous approaches and proposes a new method, which involves transforming lexical strings into more abstract features. This could be considered a form of data preprocessing or feature engineering, which falls under the category of software development (cs.SD).
